AUDIO: '[music] &gt;&gt; Hi, welcome to another video. So, if you\'ve been using AI coding agents, you\'ve probably hit this wall. You\'re running three, maybe four agents'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'locally, fixing bugs, implementing features, debugging production issues, and your machine is starting to slow down. You\'ve got 10 tabs open,'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'each with a different agent session, and you\'re constantly context switching between them, trying to remember which agent is doing what. This is the problem that Warp just solved with Oz.'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Oz is a scalable cloud coding agent with built-in orchestration. And here\'s the thing that makes it different from everything else out there. You can run as many agents as you want. They run in the cloud, so they don\'t'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'slow down your machine, and you can trigger them from anywhere. Not just from your terminal, but from Slack, Linear, GitHub, cron jobs, or even your own application code.'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'With less than 10 minutes of setup on most repos, you can have cloud agents working on your code base while you do something else entirely. So, let\'s get right into it and see how'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this actually works. There are three ways you can deploy Oz agents, which they call entry points. The first way is through listening and scheduled triggers.'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is where it gets really interesting. You can set up agents that automatically deploy when something happens. Tag it Oz in a Slack thread, and it spins up an agent to work on that'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'task. Create a Linear ticket, and an agent starts investigating. A GitHub issue comes in, and an agent triages it. You can even connect webhooks from'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Sentry. So, when an error occurs, an agent automatically starts building a fix. The second way is through the web interface at oz.warp.dev. You can manage all your agents,'

[02:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'view their progress, and even join their sessions from the browser. The third way is directly from the Warp terminal, which is probably where most of us will start.'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, let me show you the actual commands. The Warp CLI comes pre-installed when you install Warp terminal, but you can install it separately if you prefer.'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The first command you\'ll want to know is oz agent run. You pass along a prompt, and it streams back the agent response. This runs the oz agent locally, but it is also available on the Aussie'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'site for you to see what all stuff you ran, and you can then share it as well with others. So, you can view it in your Warp terminal or in the browser. Once you click that link, it loads up a Warp session with SSH,'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so it feels like you\'re having a conversation in your local terminal. You can watch the response as it streams in, or send prompts to course correct the agent as it works.'

[03:11] [scene:talk]
